, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing file shares records events related to connection to shares on a system including system shares such as C$.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"7098ecfe-3da2-45d1-94a9-c256f065200d","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 71459B3E870889576F442C4E432400A600A30DFE\r\n~~~~~\r\nFile Share:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-253321","group_tree":[{"id":"V-253321","title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-253321","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events successes.","rule_id_src":"SV-253321r991572_rule","rule_id":"SV-253321r991572","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000083","rule_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Other Object Access Events\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN11-SO-000030) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen PowerShell or a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\n\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following:\n\nObject Access >> Other Object Access Events - Success\n\nIf the system does not audit the above, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_11__STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing for other object access records events related to the management of task scheduler jobs and COM+ objects.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"7e95c7ca-7efe-40ff-b4b1-3907bcc53744","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 562793311F6A52C2F82BFBA5F96BEB983CFE618E\r\n~~~~~\r\nOther Object Access Events:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-253322","group_tree":[{"id":"V-253322","title":"SRG-OS-000462-GPOS-00206","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-253322","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events failures.","rule_id_src":"SV-253322r991572_rule","rule_id":"SV-253322r991572","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000084","rule_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit Object Access - Other Object Access Events failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Other Object Access Events\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN11-SO-000030) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\n\nOpen PowerShell or a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following:\nObject Access >> Other Object Access Events - Failure\n\nIf the system does not audit the above, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_11__STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing for other object access records events related to the management of task scheduler jobs and COM+ objects.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"51f7537f-9857-4bf6-8c3d-026da579e96b","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 562793311F6A52C2F82BFBA5F96BEB983CFE618E\r\n~~~~~\r\nOther Object Access Events:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-253323","group_tree":[{"id":"V-253323","title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-253323","severity":"medium","group_title":"The system must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage failures.","rule_id_src":"SV-253323r991583_rule","rule_id":"SV-253323r991583","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000085","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Removable Storage\" with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Security Option \"Audit: Force audit policy subcategory settings to override audit policy category settings\" must be set to \"Enabled\" (WN11-SO-000030) for the detailed auditing subcategories to be effective.\n\nUse the AuditPol tool to review the current Audit Policy configuration:\nOpen a Command Prompt with elevated privileges (\"Run as Administrator\").\nEnter \"AuditPol /get /category:*\"\n\nCompare the AuditPol settings with the following. If the system does not audit the following, this is a finding:\n\nObject Access >> Removable Storage - Failure\n\nSome virtual machines may generate excessive audit events for access to the virtual hard disk itself when this setting is enabled. This may be set to Not Configured in such cases and would not be a finding. This must be documented with the ISSO to include mitigations such as monitoring or restricting any actual removable storage connected to the VM.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_11__STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior.\n\nAuditing object access for removable media records events related to access attempts on file system objects on removable storage devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"3855dd61-0a74-4f91-8f1a-e5fb228c2caf","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: F7978927A9E4200F931B514C4D60260985327FCE\r\n~~~~~\r\nRemovable Storage:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-253324","group_tree":[{"id":"V-253324","title":"SRG-OS-000474-GPOS-00219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-253324","severity":"medium","group_title":"The system must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage successes.","rule_id_src":"SV-253324r991583_rule","rule_id":"SV-253324r991583","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000090","rule_title":"The system must be configured to audit Object Access - Removable Storage successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Setti