lated to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"046272e8-f9cb-4623-96af-41d7c1c20545","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 477EE2137395C032874C5B58F586535D026DD5E2\r\n~~~~~\r\nRegistry:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-278931","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278931","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278931","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit registry successes.","rule_id_src":"SV-278931r1135311_rule","rule_id":"SV-278931r1135311","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000586","rule_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit registry successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> \"Audit Registry\" with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit Registry auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Object Access >> Audit Registry. \n\nIf \"Audit Registry\" is not set to \"Success\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_11__STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"aeab7b9f-da9f-4d7e-8491-043afb13994a","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 477EE2137395C032874C5B58F586535D026DD5E2\r\n~~~~~\r\nRegistry:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-278932","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278932","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278932","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit sensitive privilege use successes.","rule_id_src":"SV-278932r1141916_rule","rule_id":"SV-278932r1141916","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000587","rule_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit sensitive privilege use successes.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Privilege Use >> Audit Sensitive Privilege Use with \"Success\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit Sensitive Privilege Use auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Privilege Use >> Audit Sensitive Privilege Use. \n\nIf \"Audit Sensitive Privilege Use\" is not set to \"Success\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_11__STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"9b18a8ce-b9fa-4f5a-bd5a-a3da83c14638","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: D366318ABE365344546EA78A905B8A8BAE8EA510\r\n~~~~~\r\nSensitive Privilege Use:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-278933","group_tree":[{"id":"V-278933","title":"SRG-OS-000062-GPOS-00031","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-278933","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit sensitive privilege use failures.","rule_id_src":"SV-278933r1141919_rule","rule_id":"SV-278933r1141919","rule_version":"WN11-AU-000588","rule_title":"Windows 11 must be configured to audit sensitive privilege use failures.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Privilege Use >> Audit Sensitive Privilege Use with \"Failure\" selected.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify that Audit Sensitive Privilege Use auditing has been enabled: \n\nComputer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration >> System Audit Policies >> Privilege Use >> Audit Sensitive Privilege Use. \n\nIf \"Audit Sensitive Privilege Use\" is not set to \"Failure\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_11__STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintaining an audit trail of system activity logs can help identify configuration errors, troubleshoot service disruptions, and analyze compromises that have occurred, as well as detect attacks. Audit logs are necessary to provide a trail of evidence in case the system or network is compromised. Collecting this data is essential for analyzing the security of information assets and detecting signs of suspicious and unexpected behavior. Credential validation records events related to validation tests on credentials for a user account logon.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"e7997e17-4608-4524-985e-72741af8d1ca","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: D366318ABE365344546EA78A905B8A8BAE8EA510\r\n~~~~~\r\nSensitive Privilege Use:\tNo Auditing"},{"group_id_src":"V-279688","group_tree":[{"id":"V-279688","title":"SRG-OS-000095-GPOS-00049","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-279688","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows 11 systems must block consumer account user authentication.","rule_id_src":"SV-279688r1153564_rule","rule_id":"SV-279688r1153564","rule_version":"WN11-00-000126","rule_title":"Windows 11 systems must block consumer account user authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the following Group Policy:\nComputer Configuration >> Administrative Templates >> Windows Components >> Microsoft Account \"block all consumer Microsoft account user authentication\" to \"Enabled\".\n\nFor systems managed by Intune, apply the DOD Windows 11 STIG Settings Catalog (or equivalent Intune policy) found in the Intune policy package available on cyber.mil.\nSteps to create an Intune policy:\n1. Sign in to the Intune admin center >> Devices >> Configuration >> Create >> New Policy.\n2. Platform: Windows 10 and later. Profile type: Settings Catalog, then click \"Create\".\n3. Basics: Provide a Name and Description of the profile, then click \"Next\".\n4. Configuration settings: Click \"+ Add settings\" and search for consumer under the Settings picker. Under the Administrative Templates\\Windows Components\\Microsoft account category, check the box next to \"Block all consumer Microsoft account user authentication\". Click the Enabled radio button, then click \"Next\".\n5. Scope tags: (optional), then click \"Next\".\n6. Assignments: Assign the policy to Entra security groups that contain the target users or devices, then click \"Next\".\n7. Review + create: Review the deployment summary, then click \"Create\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the \"block all consumer Microsoft account user authentication\" is enabled.\n\nRegistry Hive: HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path: \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\MicrosoftAccount\n\nValue Name: DisableUserAuth\n\nValue Type: REG_DWORD\nValue: 0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the registry value is not \"1\", this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Microsoft_Windows_11__STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is detrimental for operating systems to provide, or install by default, functionality exceeding requirements or mission objectives. These unnecessary capabilities or services are often overlooked and therefore, may remain unsecured. They increase the risk to the platform by providing additional attack vectors.\n\nOperating systems are capable of providing a wide variety of functions and services. Some of the functions and services, provided by default, may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions).\n\nThe Copilot Rewrite functionality within Notepad and Image Generation within Paint is dependent upon the use of AI credits from a Microsoft 365 Personal or Family subscription. Organizational users must not use personal accounts to login to applications on enterprise machines.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"5471","uuid":"337a9c09-9e97-4039-b021-7dc5762a0ca8","stig_uuid":"9417b45a-cc73-4ef8-8de9-659e60c46780","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows11_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: A15F5DEEC02B6405D4C1885DE2309478F2354519\r\n~~~~~\r\n'Block all consumer Microsoft account user authentication' is NOT Enabled\r\n\r\nRegistry Path:\tHKLM:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\MicrosoftAccount\r\nValue Name:\tDisableUserAuth (Not found)"}]},{"evaluate-stig":{"time":"2026-07-22T17:20:20.6747457-06:00","module":{"name":"Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks","version":"1.2026.5.14"}},"stig_name":"Microsoft Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security Security Technical Implementation Guide","display_name":"Microsoft Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security","stig_id":"Windows_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security","release_info":"Release: 2 Benchmark Date: 09 Nov 2023","version":"2","uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","reference_identifier":"5363","size":21,"rules":[{"group_id_src":"V-241989","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241989","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241989","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must be enabled when connected to a domain.","rule_id_src":"SV-241989r922928_rule","rule_id":"SV-241989r922928","rule_version":"WNFWA-000001","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must be enabled when connected to a domain.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Domain Profile tab >> State, \"Firewall state\" to \"On (recommended)\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set domainprofile state on\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles state on\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is not a member of a domain, the Domain Profile requirements can be marked NA.\n\nIf the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\DomainProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  EnableFirewall\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\DomainProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  EnableFirewall\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. This setting enables the firewall when connected to the domain.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54833","V-17415"],"ccis":["CCI-001414"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"bf6820ce-d09d-49f9-9c98-e3e3e2940cd0","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B250DCA6A1CAE59A8146BC33A4738F54215DA7E\r\n~~~~~\r\nSystem is a 'Standalone Workstation' so this requirement is NA."},{"group_id_src":"V-241990","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241990","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241990","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must be enabled when connected to a private network.","rule_id_src":"SV-241990r922930_rule","rule_id":"SV-241990r922930","rule_version":"WNFWA-000002","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must be enabled when connected to a private network.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Private Profile tab >> State, \"Firewall state\" to \"On (recommended)\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set privateprofile state on\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles state on\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\PrivateProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  EnableFirewall\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\StandardProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  EnableFirewall\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. This setting enables the firewall when connected to a private network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54849","V-17416"],"ccis":["CCI-001414"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"8b31ef2b-c460-4e8c-be16-d5bb52c5bec7","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 8C2EEB4B84402E1A36193E2EEA48CA9CC9BF8138\r\n~~~~~\r\nPrivate Profile is Enabled\r\n\r\nRegistry Path:\tHKLM:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\PrivateProfile\r\nValue Name:\tEnableFirewall\r\nValue:\t\t(NotFound)\r\nType:\t\t(NotFound)\r\n\r\nRegistry Path:\tHKLM:\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\StandardProfile\r\nValue Name:\tEnableFirewall\r\nValue:\t\t0x00000001 (1)\r\nType:\t\tREG_DWORD"},{"group_id_src":"V-241991","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241991","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241991","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must be enabled when connected to a public network.","rule_id_src":"SV-241991r922932_rule","rule_id":"SV-241991r922932","rule_version":"WNFWA-000003","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must be enabled when connected to a public network.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Public Profile tab >> State, \"Firewall state\" to \"On (recommended)\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set publicprofile state on\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles state on\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\PublicProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  EnableFirewall\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\PublicProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  EnableFirewall\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. This setting enables the firewall when connected to a public network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54855","V-17417"],"ccis":["CCI-001414"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"45e8738f-af57-4318-8649-4a41c18ad98b","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 24BF7B36FA665EE1EF93F27769F6C7989884763F\r\n~~~~~\r\nPublic Profile is Enabled\r\n\r\nRegistry Path:\tHKLM:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\PublicProfile\r\nValue Name:\tEnableFirewall\r\nValue:\t\t(NotFound)\r\nType:\t\t(NotFound)\r\n\r\nRegistry Path:\tHKLM:\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\PublicProfile\r\nValue Name:\tEnableFirewall\r\nValue:\t\t0x00000001 (1)\r\nType:\t\tREG_DWORD"},{"group_id_src":"V-241992","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241992","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241992","severity":"high","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must block unsolicited inbound connections when connected to a domain.","rule_id_src":"SV-241992r922934_rule","rule_id":"SV-241992r922934","rule_version":"WNFWA-000004","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must block unsolicited inbound connections when connected to a domain.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Domain Profile tab >> State, \"Inbound connections\" to \"Block (default)\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set domainprofile firewallpolicy blockinbound,allowoutbound\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles firewallpolicy blockinbound,allowoutbound\".\n\nBoth inbound and outbound parameters must be specified to execute this command.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is not a member of a domain, the Domain Profile requirements can be marked NA.\n\nIf the system is a member of a domain and the firewall's Domain Profile is not enabled (see V-17415), this requirement is also a finding.\n\nIf the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\DomainProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  DefaultInboundAction\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\DomainProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  DefaultInboundAction\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. Unsolicited inbound connections may be malicious attempts to gain access to a system. Unsolicited inbound connections, for which there is no rule allowing the connection, will be blocked in the domain.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54859","V-17418"],"ccis":["CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"410f6e01-4ee0-4ea8-8912-4e69983aa36f","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B250DCA6A1CAE59A8146BC33A4738F54215DA7E\r\n~~~~~\r\nSystem is a 'Standalone Workstation' so this requirement is NA."},{"group_id_src":"V-241993","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241993","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241993","severity":"medium","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must allow outbound connections, unless a rule explicitly blocks the connection when connected to a domain.","rule_id_src":"SV-241993r922936_rule","rule_id":"SV-241993r922936","rule_version":"WNFWA-000005","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must allow outbound connections, unless a rule explicitly blocks the connection when connected to a domain.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Domain Profile tab >> State, \"Outbound connections\" to \"Allow (default)\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set domainprofile firewallpolicy blockinbound,allowoutbound\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles firewallpolicy blockinbound,allowoutbound\".\n\nBoth inbound and outbound parameters must be specified to execute this command.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is not a member of a domain, the Domain Profile requirements can be marked NA.\n\nIf the system is a member of a domain and the firewall's Domain Profile is not enabled (see V-17415), this requirement is also a finding.\n\nIf the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\DomainProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  DefaultOutboundAction\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000000 (0)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\DomainProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  DefaultOutboundAction\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000000 (0)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. Outbound connections are allowed in the domain, unless a rule explicitly blocks the connection. This allows normal outbound communication, which could be restricted as necessary with additional rules.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54863","V-17419"],"ccis":["CCI-001094"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"fdd15efb-7f89-4028-9c22-15e5bd9f630b","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B250DCA6A1CAE59A8146BC33A4738F54215DA7E\r\n~~~~~\r\nSystem is a 'Standalone Workstation' so this requirement is NA."},{"group_id_src":"V-241994","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241994","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241994","severity":"low","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security log size must be configured for domain connections.","rule_id_src":"SV-241994r922938_rule","rule_id":"SV-241994r922938","rule_version":"WNFWA-000009","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security log size must be configured for domain connections.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Domain Profile tab >> Logging (select Customize), \"Size limit (KB):\" to \"16,384\" or greater.\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh command may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set domainprofile logging maxfilesize 16384\" or greater.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is not a member of a domain, the Domain Profile requirements can be marked NA.\n\nIf the system is a member of a domain and the firewall's Domain Profile is not enabled (see V-17415), this requirement is also a finding.\n\nIf the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\DomainProfile\\Logging\\\n\nValue Name:  LogFileSize\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00004000 (16384) (or greater)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\DomainProfile\\Logging\\\n\nValue Name:  LogFileSize\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00004000 (16384) (or greater)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. The firewall log file size for a domain connection will be set to ensure enough capacity is allocated for audit data.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54874","V-17425"],"ccis":["CCI-000140"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"0e99aa05-d459-4818-81ce-f065b7e7edb3","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B250DCA6A1CAE59A8146BC33A4738F54215DA7E\r\n~~~~~\r\nSystem is a 'Standalone Workstation' so this requirement is NA."},{"group_id_src":"V-241995","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241995","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241995","severity":"low","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must log dropped packets when connected to a domain.","rule_id_src":"SV-241995r922940_rule","rule_id":"SV-241995r922940","rule_version":"WNFWA-000010","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must log dropped packets when connected to a domain.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Domain Profile tab >> Logging (select Customize), \"Log dropped packets\" to \"Yes\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set domainprofile logging droppedconnections enable\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles logging droppedconnections enable\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is not a member of a domain, the Domain Profile requirements can be marked NA.\n\nIf the system is a member of a domain and the firewall's Domain Profile is not enabled (see V-17415), this requirement is also a finding.\n\nIf the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\DomainProfile\\Logging\\\n\nValue Name:  LogDroppedPackets\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\DomainProfile\\Logging\\\n\nValue Name:  LogDroppedPackets\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. Logging of dropped packets for a domain connection will be enabled to maintain an audit trail of potential issues.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54877","V-17426"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"a88d8c7a-eed8-42e1-84ba-6622270527b9","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B250DCA6A1CAE59A8146BC33A4738F54215DA7E\r\n~~~~~\r\nSystem is a 'Standalone Workstation' so this requirement is NA."},{"group_id_src":"V-241996","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241996","title":"SRG-OS-000327-GPOS-00127","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241996","severity":"low","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must log successful connections when connected to a domain.","rule_id_src":"SV-241996r922942_rule","rule_id":"SV-241996r922942","rule_version":"WNFWA-000011","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must log successful connections when connected to a domain.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Domain Profile tab >> Logging (select Customize), \"Log successful connections\" to \"Yes\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set domainprofile logging allowedconnections enable\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles logging allowedconnections enable\".","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the system is not a member of a domain, the Domain Profile requirements can be marked NA.\n\nIf the system is a member of a domain and the firewall's Domain Profile is not enabled (see V-17415), this requirement is also a finding.\n\nIf the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\DomainProfile\\Logging\\\n\nValue Name:  LogSuccessfulConnections\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\DomainProfile\\Logging\\\n\nValue Name:  LogSuccessfulConnections\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. Logging of successful connections for a domain connection will be enabled to maintain an audit trail if issues are discovered.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54878","V-17427"],"ccis":["CCI-001462"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"d8855630-cbb8-4e01-8f28-8f20b2307ef0","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 1B250DCA6A1CAE59A8146BC33A4738F54215DA7E\r\n~~~~~\r\nSystem is a 'Standalone Workstation' so this requirement is NA."},{"group_id_src":"V-241997","group_tree":[{"id":"V-241997","title":"SRG-OS-000480-GPOS-00227","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-241997","severity":"high","group_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must block unsolicited inbound connections when connected to a private network.","rule_id_src":"SV-241997r922944_rule","rule_id":"SV-241997r922944","rule_version":"WNFWA-000012","rule_title":"Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security must block unsolicited inbound connections when connected to a private network.","fix_text":"The preferred method of configuring the firewall settings is with a policy, particularly in a domain environment.\n\nConfigure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security >> Windows Defender Firewall Properties (this link will be in the right pane) >> Private Profile tab >> State, \"Inbound connections\" to \"Block (default)\".\n\nIn addition to using policies, systems may also be configured using the firewall GUI or Netsh commands. These methods may be more appropriate for standalone systems.\n\nThe configuration settings in the GUI are the same as those specified in the policy above. Microsoft Defender Firewall Properties will be a link in the center pane after opening Microsoft Defender Firewall with Advanced Security.\n\nThe following Netsh commands may also be used to configure this setting:\n\n\"Netsh advfirewall set privateprofile firewallpolicy blockinbound,allowoutbound\".\nor\n\"Netsh advfirewall set allprofiles firewallpolicy blockinbound,allowoutbound\".\n\nBoth inbound and outbound parameters must be specified to execute this command.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"If the firewall's Private Profile is not enabled (see V-17416), this requirement is also a finding.\n\nIf the following policy-based registry value exists and is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\PrivateProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  DefaultInboundAction\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)\n\nIf the policy-based registry value does not exist, verify the following registry value. If it is not configured as specified, this is a finding.\n\nRegistry Hive:  HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\nRegistry Path:  \\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\SharedAccess\\Parameters\\FirewallPolicy\\StandardProfile\\\n\nValue Name:  DefaultInboundAction\n\nType:  REG_DWORD\nValue:  0x00000001 (1)","check_content_ref":{"href":"Windows_Defender_Firewall_with_Advanced_Security_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A firewall provides a line of defense against attack. To be effective, it must be enabled and properly configured. Unsolicited inbound connections may be malicious attempts to gain access to a system. Unsolicited inbound connections, for which there is no rule allowing the connection, will be blocked on a private network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-54879","V-17428"],"ccis":["CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"5363","uuid":"39f20284-70f8-45f5-a259-30d97d43680c","stig_uuid":"50953bc4-21dd-4c67-8588-c0b756084b52","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-WindowsFirewall_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/22/2026\r\nResultHash: 46F8004C22582DFECDD46187338285ED4411A0FB\r\n~~~~~\r\nPrivate Profile is Enabled\r\n\r\nNo compliant setting found:\r\n---------------------------\r\nRegistry Path:\tHKLM:\\SOFTWARE\\Policies\\Microsoft\\WindowsFirewall\\PrivateProfile\r\nValue Name:\tDefaultInboundAction\r\nValue:\t\t(NotFound)\r\nType:\t\t(NotFound)\r\n\r\nRegistry Path:\tHKLM:\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services\\S